@robbyoconnor: Hey Robby, MIT 6.001 is a popular course which is based on the same book - SICP. The version on OCW even has videos by authors themselves - http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/electrical-engineering-and-computer-science/6-001-structure-and-interpretation-of-computer-programs-spring-2005/video-lectures/. I feel the OCW course is more comprehensive than this one.  Let me know what you think.

@awelch83  .DS_Store "(short for Desktop Services Store)[1] is a hidden file with a proprietary format created by OS X to store custom attributes of a folder such as the position of icons or the choice of a background image"  [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.DS_Store)

Bottomline, they will keep coming back because they are generated automatically by the OS. To avoid that, you should use  `gitignore` files. This [link](http://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore) will help you overcome this issue.

@prakhar1989 To answer your concerns from #93, I agree that courses which offer assignments and lectures, in addition to readings, are more useful. I still think, however, that CS 6650 serves a purpose, because this subject matter isn't currently addressed by any other course listed in the readme. In the future, if someone finds a course on this subject that does have assignments to go with it, they will hopefully delete my entry and replace it with their own. Aside from that, I also got rid of the extra bullet point that I somehow created at line 615, in pr #93.
